summary:
The available evidence shows no support for a functional or physical interaction between MOV10 and RNASEH2 in promoting L1 retrotransposition; instead, RNASEH2 functions in genome maintenance through DNA repair mechanisms unrelated to enhancing retroelement activity. Therefore, their combined action does not drive L1 retrotransposition.  
\boxed{B}

The interaction between MOV10 and RNASEH2 does not promote L1 retrotransposition because neither protein is shown to have a documented functional or physical link in this process. Instead, RNASEH2 supports genome stability via DNA repair, while MOV10 regulates RNA metabolism without demonstrated involvement in activating L1 elements.  

